on, while pro-choice activists invested too much in Roe at the expense of political mobilization. Further illuminating these cases, as well as the ongoing fight for same-sex marriage rights, Rosenberg also marshals impressive evidence to overturn the common assumption that even unsuccessful litigation can advance a cause by raising its profile. Directly addressing its critics in a new conclusion, The Hollow Hope, Second Edition promises to reignite for a new generation the national debate it sparked seventeen years ago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aCourtszUnited States. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited States. 0aSocial change. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 0aWomen's rightszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asame-sex marriage, homosexuality, gay rights, courts, law, legal system, reform, social change, litigation, supreme court, roe v wade, brown board of education, desegregation, politics, pro-choice, abortion, political movements, race, racism, discrimination, women, gender, reapportionment, environment, loving virginia, miscegenation, nonfiction, history, mobilization.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226726687423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226726687/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles